BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260317T131510Z
DTSTART:20260324T110000Z
DTEND:20260324T113000Z
SUMMARY:Dapr in the AI Era: Orchestrating Complex Multi-agent Workflows With Automatic Recovery - Yaron Schneider\, Diagrid
DESCRIPTION:In this session we'll learn how Dapr enables agent frameworks like OpenAI agents\, AWS Strands\, CrewAI and LangGraph to run reliably in the face of network errors\, full cluster shutdowns and even complete cloud outages. Dapr's workflow\, pub/sub and state APIs can be integrated as first-class primitives into the agent runtime of your choice\, enabling Ops teams to make their AI systems ready for production and multi-cloud architectures.
CATEGORIES:MAINTAINER TRACK
LOCATION:E103-105\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:7506253eb12615d2ff4195d0bf5c64bc
URL:http://kccnceu2026.sched.com/event/7506253eb12615d2ff4195d0bf5c64bc
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260317T131510Z
DTSTART:20260324T110000Z
DTEND:20260324T113000Z
SUMMARY:In Falco's Nest: The Evolution of Cloud Native Runtime Security - Iacopo Rozzo\, Sysdig; Aldo Lacuku\, Kong Inc.
DESCRIPTION:Falco\, the Cloud Native Runtime Security project\, is constantly evolving to meet the demands of modern cloud environments. This maintainer track session\, led by the Falco maintainers\, will dive deep into the latest advancements and the strategic direction of the project. We will focus on two major areas of growth: the introduction of the new Falco Operator and the new features that enhance Falco's performance and reliability. The new Falco Operator simplifies the deployment\, configuration\, and management of Falco across Kubernetes clusters\, making it easier than ever for users to secure their runtime environments at scale. Furthermore\, we will explore the most significant new features integrated into Falco. This includes performance optimizations for high-throughput environments. The session will also touch upon community contributions\, ecosystem integrations\, and the roadmap for the upcoming release.
CATEGORIES:MAINTAINER TRACK
LOCATION:G102-103\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:8baff91284b0e2034da133b8441e7919
URL:http://kccnceu2026.sched.com/event/8baff91284b0e2034da133b8441e7919
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260317T131510Z
DTSTART:20260324T110000Z
DTEND:20260324T113000Z
SUMMARY:Vitess: More Data\, No Problems - Matt Lord & Rohit Nayak\, PlanetScale
DESCRIPTION:You may have already bumped up against cases where operating at your current scale prove challenging: schema changes\, upgrades\, failovers\, performance\, backups\, data migrations\, and more. Vitess has allowed some of the biggest tech companies on the planet to operate massive data storage layers. It provides the automation\, the tooling\, and the feature set necessary to operate at virtually unlimited scale. And its cloud native\, automated\, self-healing nature allows you to achieve this with a small team of engineers! In this talk we will cover some of the key aspects of Vitess that allow you to confidently and successfully meet your current and future database operation needs as your organization grows and your data expands along with it.
CATEGORIES:MAINTAINER TRACK
LOCATION:Amtrium 1+2\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:b797a8e09a33b6738d2d9acc24770e2d
URL:http://kccnceu2026.sched.com/event/b797a8e09a33b6738d2d9acc24770e2d
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260317T131510Z
DTSTART:20260324T110000Z
DTEND:20260324T113000Z
SUMMARY:WIT Happens: Exploring the Latest Evolution of the SPIFFE and WIMSE Workload Identity Standards. - Noah Stride\, Teleport & Arndt Schwenkschuster\, Defakto Security
DESCRIPTION:Workload identity is evolving. The IETF WIMSE Working Group has been standardizing the Workload Identity Token (WIT): a new credential format designed to address gaps in current workload-to-workload authentication. In 2026\, SPIFFE and SPIRE will adopt WIT as a native credential type alongside existing JWT and X.509 options. But\, what exactly makes WIT different? In this talk\, we’ll give a brief overview of SPIFFE and WIMSE\, and explore how they fit together. We’ll recap the existing JWT and X509 credential types and dive into the WIT\, exploring its structure\, security properties and presentation methods\, and compare this against X509 and JWT. And\, with any luck\, we’ll demo how the WIT can be used for workload to workload authentication. Whether you’re already using SPIFFE\, or\, are interested in the workload identity space\, this session is for you!
CATEGORIES:MAINTAINER TRACK
LOCATION:E106-108\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:40e24e529b40a399be6886ab29a6b433
URL:http://kccnceu2026.sched.com/event/40e24e529b40a399be6886ab29a6b433
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260317T131510Z
DTSTART:20260324T110000Z
DTEND:20260324T113000Z
SUMMARY:When OTTL Goes Off the Rails: Debugging Transformations with Confidence - Edmo Vamerlatti Costa\, Elastic & Tyler Helmuth\, Honeycomb
DESCRIPTION:Ever written an OpenTelemetry Transformation Language (OTTL) statement that looked right but went completely off the rails when you ran it? You’re not alone. Testing and troubleshooting OTTL can be tricky\, especially when it’s unclear how your telemetry data is being interpreted and transformed under the hood.\n\nIn this session\, we’ll demonstrate how to keep your transformations running smoothly. Using the OpenTelemetry Collector’s built-in tools and the OTTL Playground (https://ottl.run)\, we’ll validate\, debug\, and fine-tune statements using real-world examples. Along the way\, we’ll uncover hidden issues\, explain unexpected behavior\, and explore strategies to guide your transformations back on track.\n\nExpect live demos\, debug logs\, a few intentional derailments\, and practical tips to make your next troubleshooting session smoother\, and maybe even a little https://ottl.fun.
CATEGORIES:OBSERVABILITY
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room G\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:311ed775421c436be4a895da434410a8
URL:http://kccnceu2026.sched.com/event/311ed775421c436be4a895da434410a8
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260317T131510Z
DTSTART:20260324T110000Z
DTEND:20260324T113000Z
SUMMARY:5000 Kubernetes Clusters\, 5 Minutes: Walmart’s Secret to Rapid Edge Deployments with Argo - Yug Gupta\, Walmart Global Tech
DESCRIPTION:Imagine deploying applications across 5\,000+ Kubernetes edge clusters in under 5 minutes\, despite severe internet bandwidth constraints. In this case study\, we unveil how we turned this challenge into an opportunity by harnessing the power of Argo Workflows. Our edge clusters\, located in retail stores across the U.S.\, required a deployment strategy that could overcome slow internet speeds and avoid business disruptions during operational hours.\n\nWe’ll show how we cut fleet-wide deploys to ~5 minutes P95 by pre-seeding OCI images to local caches\, time-windowing Helm releases\, and enforcing digest-pinned\, policy-gated rollouts with an intelligent pull+push mechanism. The result was a highly efficient\, batch-based deployment across a massive fleet of edge clusters\, completed in record time.\n\nYou’ll leave with YAMLs and a runbook you can try in staging\, plus the pitfalls we hit first (cold caches\, egress bottlenecks\, etc) and the pragmatic fixes that made it fast and predictable.
CATEGORIES:OPERATIONS + PERFORMANCE
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room D\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:fec46aa65d4e2ab5814a8855dd4a6c1b
URL:http://kccnceu2026.sched.com/event/fec46aa65d4e2ab5814a8855dd4a6c1b
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260317T131510Z
DTSTART:20260324T110000Z
DTEND:20260324T113000Z
SUMMARY:Kubernetes Autopsy: Live Debugging a Cluster Meltdown - Sandeep Kanabar\, Gen; Aditi Gupta\, Disney+ Hotstar; Anshika Gupta\, Independent
DESCRIPTION:What happens when a Kubernetes cluster spirals? In this technical deep-dive\, we'll reconstruct a real-world cluster catastrophe from the digital crime scene it left behind.\n\nWatch as we perform a live forensic analysis of a cascading failure: a memory leak that triggered an OOMKill\, which destabilized etcd\, which corrupted state\, which triggered a controller storm\, which brought down the control plane. Using actual logs\, metrics\, and traces\, we'll reverse-engineer the incident minute-by-minute\, revealing how seemingly unrelated symptoms connect into a devastating chain reaction.\n\nYou'll learn advanced debugging techniques using kubectl\, crictl\, etcdctl\, and eBPF-based observability tools. We'll explore how to read the "black box" data Kubernetes components leave behind\, identify root causes hidden in cascading symptoms\, and build runbooks that prevent similar disasters.\n\nThis isn't post-mortem theater—it's about reading the signs before your cluster writes its own obituary.
CATEGORIES:OPERATIONS + PERFORMANCE
LOCATION:Elicium 2\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:2e22c03ced7c9f271cc8c93413a23ab8
URL:http://kccnceu2026.sched.com/event/2e22c03ced7c9f271cc8c93413a23ab8
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260317T131510Z
DTSTART:20260324T110000Z
DTEND:20260324T113000Z
SUMMARY:API is the New SSH: Forging a Zero-Trust VM Platform on Kubernetes - Evangelista Tragni\, Devoteam
DESCRIPTION:Many organizations want to embrace cloud-native principles\, but they can't abandon virtual machines just yet. How can we bridge these two worlds without sacrificing security and automation? In this session\, we will guide you through our journey of building a multi-tenant virtualization platform entirely on Kubernetes\, designed from the ground up to be secure\, immutable\, and declaratively managed.\n\nYou will discover KubeVirt as a main pillar to orchestrate VMs natively on kubernetes\, but all this built on a Modern and secure OS and next to it you will discover a lot of project that are expanding different capabilities and features for our VM PLATFORM.\n\nJoin this session to get a concrete roadmap for building a modern\, resilient\, and truly cloud-native VM platform.
CATEGORIES:PLATFORM ENGINEERING
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room C\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:4316ced9317557722617ff1bdab83a5c
URL:http://kccnceu2026.sched.com/event/4316ced9317557722617ff1bdab83a5c
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260317T131510Z
DTSTART:20260324T110000Z
DTEND:20260324T113000Z
SUMMARY:Flipping the Curve: A Platform Engineer's Guide to Unlocking the Silent 80% - Michael Reichenbach\, 1KOMMA5°
DESCRIPTION:Many platform engineering teams unknowingly create an "inverse productivity curve": their platforms are highly effective for a small group of experts but leave the vast majority of their developers behind. This happens because platform engineers intuitively build for their peers\, the most vocal 20% of users who prefer high-end but often highly complex solutions\, instead of for the silent 80% majority who need simple\, straightforward solutions.\n\nThis session provides a practical guide and case studies to break this cycle using "guerrilla product thinking." Attendees will learn practical\, low-effort tactics to shift their focus\, such as visualizing their user base to identify the true majority and conducting targeted interviews with silent developers to uncover the most impactful problems. The talk will equip every platform engineer with the mindset and tools needed to flip the productivity curve\, eliminate expert bottlenecks\, and build platforms that accelerate the entire organization.
CATEGORIES:PLATFORM ENGINEERING
LOCATION:F002-005\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:9d430e536a950c1b8a2427d2fc4d1b75
URL:http://kccnceu2026.sched.com/event/9d430e536a950c1b8a2427d2fc4d1b75
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260317T131510Z
DTSTART:20260324T110000Z
DTEND:20260324T113000Z
SUMMARY:No Shame\, Just Pain: How We Migrated Away From Kubernetes 1.16 in 2025 - Jannis Relakis & Michael Seiwald-McCarty\, Celonis
DESCRIPTION:Until recently\, while the world was talking WASM and AI-driven ops\, we were still running Kubernetes 1.16\; on over fifty clusters\, across six flavors\, and three cloud providers.\n\nThis talk is the story of how we dug ourselves out of that hole: a multi-year\, zero-downtime migration that forced us to face years of technical debt\, align dozens of teams\, and rethink how we manage clusters at scale.\n\nI’ll share how we launched a zero-downtime migration for hundreds of workloads\, untangled messy dependencies\, built “the wormhole” (our Envoy-based cross-cluster bridge)\, and designed a new fleet architecture across EKS\, AKS\, and GKE. Along the way we met deprecated APIs\, abandoned components\, and a few stubborn Frankenstein clusters.\n\nThis is not a “look how shiny our platform is” story. It’s a confession from someone who sat through KubeCon talks for years drooling over features we couldn’t use. There’s no shame. Just lessons\, empathy\, and a lot of pain turned into progress.
CATEGORIES:PLATFORM ENGINEERING
LOCATION:Forum\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:b3716c6eb82afd1efaaa0a94dec865d9
URL:http://kccnceu2026.sched.com/event/b3716c6eb82afd1efaaa0a94dec865d9
END:VEVENT
